{
  "id": "algebra-2-ch01-sec06",
  "title": "Chapter Review",
  "chapter": 1,
  "section": 6,
  "book": "algebra-2",
  "epigraph": {
    "text": "Test all things; hold fast what is good.",
    "reference": "1 Thessalonians 5:21"
  },
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "This chapter has reviewed the foundational skills of equation and \ninequality solving that you developed in Algebra 1. These skills will \nbe essential throughout Algebra 2 as we encounter more complex equations \ninvolving quadratics, exponentials, logarithms, and trigonometry."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Key Concepts Summary"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Chapter Review Exercises"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "**Section 1.1: Linear Equations**"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve each equation."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$5x - 8 = 17$",
        "$3(x + 2) - 4x = 5$",
        "$\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{3} + \\frac{x}{4} = 7$",
        "$0.4x - 1.2 = 0.6x + 0.8$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Classify and solve (if possible)."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$2(x + 5) = 2x + 10$",
        "$3x - 7 = 3x + 2$",
        "$4(x - 1) = 2(2x + 3)$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "**Section 1.2: Linear Inequalities**"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve and graph each inequality."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$3x - 5 > 7$",
        "$-2x + 4 \\leq 10$",
        "$4 - 3x \\geq 13$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve each compound inequality."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$-4 < 2x + 2 \\leq 8$",
        "$3x - 1 < 5$ and $2x + 3 > 1$",
        "$x + 2 < -1$ or $x - 3 > 2$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "**Section 1.3: Absolute Value Equations**"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve each equation."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$\\abs{x - 5} = 8$",
        "$\\abs{2x + 1} = 7$",
        "$3\\abs{x - 2} = 15$",
        "$\\abs{x + 3} = \\abs{2x - 1}$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve or state no solution."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$\\abs{4x - 1} = -5$",
        "$\\abs{x - 2} + 4 = 1$",
        "$\\abs{x + 1} = 3x - 5$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "**Section 1.4: Absolute Value Inequalities**"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve and write in interval notation."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$\\abs{x} < 6$",
        "$\\abs{x - 3} \\leq 4$",
        "$\\abs{2x + 1} > 5$",
        "$\\abs{3x - 2} \\geq 7$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$\\abs{x + 2} < -1$",
        "$\\abs{5 - x} \\geq 0$",
        "$2\\abs{x - 1} + 3 < 9$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "**Section 1.5: Literal Equations**"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve for the indicated variable."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$A = \\frac{1}{2}h(b_1 + b_2)$ for $b_1$",
        "$V = \\pi r^2 h$ for $h$",
        "$y = mx + b$ for $m$",
        "$F = \\frac{9}{5}C + 32$ for $C$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve for $x$."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "$ax + b = cx - d$",
        "$\\displaystyle\\frac{x}{a} + \\frac{x}{b} = 1$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Mixed Practice"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve: $\\displaystyle\\frac{2x + 1}{3} - \\frac{x - 2}{6} = 2$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve: $4(2x - 3) - 5 = 3(x + 2) + x$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve and graph: $-1 < 3 - 2x \\leq 9$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve: $\\abs{3x - 2} = 10$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve: $\\abs{x + 5} = \\abs{2x - 1}$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve: $\\abs{2x - 1} \\leq 7$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve: $\\abs{4 - x} > 2$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve for $h$: $V = \\frac{1}{3}\\pi r^2 h$"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Solve for $a$: $\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{a} + \\frac{1}{b} = \\frac{1}{c}$"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Applications"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A phone plan costs \\$25 per month plus \\$0.10 per text message. Another \nplan costs \\$35 per month with unlimited texting. For how many texts \nis the first plan cheaper?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A student has test scores of 78, 85, and 90. What range of scores on \nthe fourth test will result in an average between 80 and 90 (inclusive)?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "A manufacturing process produces bolts with a target diameter of 0.75 \ninches. Quality control rejects any bolt whose diameter differs from \nthe target by more than 0.008 inches. Write an absolute value inequality \nand solve for the acceptable diameters."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The speed of sound in air depends on temperature. At $0°$C, sound travels \nat approximately 331 meters per second. For each degree Celsius increase, \nthe speed increases by about 0.6 m/s. The formula is $v = 331 + 0.6T$."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "Solve for $T$ in terms of $v$.",
        "At what temperature does sound travel at 350 m/s?",
        "If thunder is heard 3 seconds after lightning is seen at 20°C, \n how far away did the lightning strike?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The cost to produce $x$ widgets is $C = 500 + 3x$ dollars, and the \nrevenue from selling them is $R = 8x$ dollars."
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "For what values of $x$ is revenue greater than cost (profit)?",
        "At least how many widgets must be sold to make a profit?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Chapter 1 Test Practice"
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "ordered": true,
      "items": [
        "Solve: $4(2x - 3) - 5 = 3(x + 2) + x$",
        "Solve: $\\displaystyle\\frac{2x + 1}{3} - \\frac{x - 2}{6} = 2$",
        "Classify as one solution, no solution, or infinitely many: \n $3(x + 4) - 2x = x + 12$",
        "Solve and graph: $-2x + 5 > 11$",
        "Solve: $-1 < 3 - 2x \\leq 9$",
        "Solve: $\\abs{3x - 2} = 10$",
        "Solve: $\\abs{x + 5} = \\abs{2x - 1}$",
        "Solve: $\\abs{2x - 1} \\leq 7$",
        "Solve: $\\abs{4 - x} > 2$",
        "Solve for $h$: $V = \\frac{1}{3}\\pi r^2 h$",
        "Solve for $a$: $\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{a} + \\frac{1}{b} = \\frac{1}{c}$",
        "A phone plan costs \\$25 per month plus \\$0.10 per text. If \n another plan costs \\$35 per month with unlimited texting, for how \n many texts is the first plan cheaper?",
        "The sides of a triangle are consecutive even integers. If the \n perimeter is at most 48, find all possible values for the shortest side.",
        "Solve: $\\abs{x - 4} + \\abs{x + 2} = 10$",
        "For what values of $c$ does $\\abs{x - 2} = c$ have exactly two solutions?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Looking Ahead"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "In Chapter 2, we will apply these equation-solving skills to \n**systems of linear equations**—two or more equations that \nmust be satisfied simultaneously. You will learn multiple methods \n(graphing, substitution, elimination, matrices) and discover that \nsystems can model fascinating real-world situations from economics \nto chemistry to network flows."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "The skills from this chapter—especially isolating variables and \nworking with compound inequalities—will be essential for success."
    }
  ]
}